There are 32 general-purpose registers that are each 64 bits wide in RV64I. Each register has a role defined by the integer register convention . Basically, an emulator doesn't care about the roles of a register except zero (x0) and sp (x2) registers. The zero register x0 is hardwired with all bits equal to 0. The sp register x2 is a stack pointer. A stack is a data structure mainly located at the end of the address space. It is especially used to store local variables. A stack pointer keeps track of a stack. A value of a stack pointer is subtracted in a function prologue , so we need to set it up with a non-0 value. main.rs // Set the register x2 with the size of a memory when a CPU is
// instantiated.
regs[2] = MEMORY_SIZE; // 1024 * 1024 * 128 (128MiB). // Reset the value of register x0 with 0 in each cycle to mimic that
// register x0 is hardwired with all bits equal to 0.
self.regs[0] = 0;

